The '''Milan Metro Line One''' (''Linea Uno'' in [[Italian language|Italian]]) is the first underground [[rapid transit]] line built in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]. It is part of the [[Milan Metro]] and it is operated by [[Azienda Trasporti Milanesi|ATM]]. Works on the line began in 1957, and the first part was opened on 1 November 1964,<ref name=atmstoria>{{cite web|title=ATM - Storia|url=http://www.atm-mi.it/it/IlGruppo/LaStoria/Pagine/ChiEravamo.aspx|publisher=Azienda Trasporti Milanesi|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=cartamobilita2011>{{cite web|title=Carta della mobilit<U+00E0> 2011|url=http://www.atm-mi.it/it/IlGruppo/ChiSiamo/Documents/carta_della_mobilita2011.pdf|publisher=Azienda Trasporti Milanesi|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> running from Sesto Marelli to Lotto station. The line is also called '''Red Line''' (''Linea Rossa'' in Italian), as it is visually identified by red signs. Due to its premiership, the line gave its red color to the Milan Metro logo.

==Route==
The line runs underground from the northern suburb of [[Sesto San Giovanni]] to the city centre, then to western district with two different branches, one to northwest to [[Rho]], the other to the west to Bisceglie. It is {{convert|27|km|abbr=on}} long and serves 38 underground stations.<ref name=CR1>{{cite news|title=Linea M1 di Milano: il nuovo segnalamento entra in attivit<U+00E0> durante il ponte del 1<U+00B0>novembre|url=http://www.cityrailways.it/home/2011/10/31/linea-m1-di-milano-il-nuovo-segnalamento-entra-in-attivita-d.html|accessdate=3 November 2011|newspaper=I binari - CityRailways|date=31 October 2011}}</ref>

Key points served by the line are ''[[Piazza Duomo|Duomo]]'', considered the center of Milan; [[Castello Sforzesco]] (with [[Cairoli (Milan Metro)|Cairoli]] station); ''[[Milano Cadorna railway station|Cadorna]]'', one of the busiest station in Milan and in Italy; ''[[Corso Buenos Aires]]'' (with stations [[Porta Venezia (Milan Metro)|Porta Venezia]], [[Lima (Milan Metro)|Lima]] and [[Loreto (Milan Metro)|Loreto]]), an important shopping street; and [[Fiera Milano|Rho Fiera]], one of the largest fairground in the world.<ref name=about>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://www.fieramilano.it/portal/page?_pageid=36,39304&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL|publisher=FieraMilano|accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref>

==History==
On 6 April 1952 the city administration asked for a project of a metro system and on 6 October 1955 a new company, Metropolitana Milanese, was created to manage the construction of the new infrastructure.<ref name=mmstoria>{{cite web|title=La storia della linea 1|url=http://www.metropolitanamilanese.it/pub/page/it/MM/metropolitane_milano?contentId=904|publisher=Metropolitana Milanese Spa|accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref>  The project was funded with [[Italian lira|<U+20A4>]] 500 million from the municipality and the rest from a loan. The construction site of the first line was opened in ''viale Monte Rosa'' on 4 May 1957.<ref name=mmstoria /> Stations on the new line were designed by Albini-Helg architecture studio. [[Bob Noorda]] designed the famous signaling.<ref name=mmstoria />

The line from ''Lotto'' to ''Sesto Marelli'' (21 stations) opened on 1 November 1964, after 7 years of construction works.

==Rolling stock==
There are 3 types of trains running on the line: the original first series trains, revamped original trains and the new [[AnsaldoBreda]] ''[[AnsaldoBreda Meneghino|Meneghino]]'' trains. The track gauge is the 1,435&nbsp;mm [[standard gauge]]. The entire line is electrified by means of a [[third rail|third]] or [[fourth rail]] at 750 V.<ref name=metrobits>{{cite web|title=Milan Metro|url=http://mic-ro.com/metro/metrocity.html?city=Milan|publisher=metrobits.org|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>

Among the 63 trains running on the line, 20 entered service between 1964 (opening of the line) and 1970. Those trains are planned to be replaced by new Meneghino trains in the next few years. There are 17 Meneghino trains already operational as of March 2012.<ref name=oldtrains />

==Extension==
An extension on the north from [[Sesto 1<U+00B0> Maggio (Milan Metro)|Sesto Primo Maggio]] to [[Monza]] is currently under construction. It is expected to be completed by 2015 before the [[Expo 2015|Milan Expo]].<ref name=tomonza>{{cite news|last=Baron|first=Ferdinando|title=M1 fino a Monza, partiti i lavori|url=http://milano.corriere.it/milano/notizie/cronaca/11_luglio_5/metro-monza-partiti-lavori-1901019985113.shtml|accessdate=5 October 2011|newspaper=Corriere della Sera|date=5 July 2011}}</ref> The new section will be {{convert|1.9|km|abbr=on}} long with 2 stations (''Sesto Restellone'' and ''Monza Bettola''), entirely underground. The total cost will be <U+20AC>206 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stella|first=Armando|title=Metr<U+00F2> per Monza, ad aprile primi cantieri|url=http://milano.corriere.it/milano/notizie/cronaca/11_marzo_14/monza-metro-190217793326.shtml|accessdate=5 October 2011|newspaper=Corriere della Sera|date=14 March 2011}}</ref>

